=== 评价 ===

* 汉斯力克：有那么一阵子这首协奏曲还算是音乐，比例恰当，而且不无才气。但很快地，野蛮占了上风，横肆暴虐直到第一乐章结束。小提琴不再是演奏出来的，它被硬生生地拉扯，被撕裂粉碎，被击打得青一块紫一块。不知是否有人能征服这些可怕的困难，但我确信布罗茨基先生让自己和听众都成为了牺牲品。柔板{{NoteTag|指第二乐章}}几乎与我们和解，让我们改变对这部作品的不好印象，但它突然过快地结束，让第三乐章带领我们来到粗犷而嘈杂的俄罗斯集市的欢闹中。我们可以看到狂放下流的嘴脸，听到恶语相向的咒骂，闻到劣等白兰地的酒味。{{link-en|弗里德里希·西奥多·维舍尔|Friedrich Theodor Vischer|弗里德里希·维舍尔}}在提到某些油画时说“有些画臭得刺痛人的眼睛”，柴可夫斯基的小提琴协奏曲第一次使我们可怕地认识到，有些音乐也可以臭得刺痛人的耳朵。<ref name=":5" /><ref name="Steinberg" />{{Rp|487}}<ref name=":10" />{{Rp|129}}<ref name="Dilemma" /><ref>Edward Hanslick, ''Music Criticisms 1850-1900,'' 由 Henry Pleasants 编辑并翻译为英文 (Baltimore: Penguin Books, 1963)</ref>
* 奥尔：
** 在所有文艺界的音乐厅里，在每一个教授正规小提琴演奏的琴房中，（这部协奏曲）都占有一席之地。{{NoteTag|原文：{{lang-en|... the great Russian composer's Concerto in D major has held its own in all the concert halls of the cultured world, and in every studio where rational violin-playing is taught.}}}}<ref name="Violinistic" />{{Rp|13-30}}<ref>{{Cite book|title=Violin Master Works and their Interpretation|last=Auer|first=Leopold|publisher=Carl Fischer, Inc.|year=1925|isbn=|location=纽约|pages=}}</ref>
** 这部协奏曲走向了世界，这是最重要的。不可能让所有人都满意。{{NoteTag|原文：{{lang-en|The concerto has made its way in the world, and after all, that is the most important thing. It is impossible to please everybody.}}}}<ref name="Steinberg" />{{Rp|485-486}}<ref name=":6" />
* {{Link-en|Antje Weithaas}}：了解作曲家的背景和性格是很重要的。并非所有的作品都和个人有关，但在这部作品中，你能听到，困在无爱的婚姻中，他陷入了抑郁的危机。{{NoteTag|原文：{{lang-en|It's always important to understand the composer's background and personality; not all pieces are personal but in this one you can hear that he's in a crisis of depression, of being trapped in a loveless marriage.}}}}<ref name=":15">{{Cite web|title=5 views on Tchaikovsky's Violin Concerto|url=https://www.thestrad.com/artists/5-views-on-tchaikovskys-violin-concerto/8928.article|access-date=2021-07-19|date=2019-05-07|last=|work=The Strad|language=en|archive-date=2021-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210720142857/https://www.thestrad.com/artists/5-views-on-tchaikovskys-violin-concerto/8928.article|dead-url=no}}</ref>
* {{Link-en|Augustin Hadelich}}：它是小提琴曲目中最折磨人的协奏曲。它自始至终情感强烈，即使在轻柔的片段中也是如此；巨大的技术挑战，对体力也有要求。演奏这部作品前，我总要热身至少45分钟，慢慢练习棘手的乐段，直到我感到舒适为止。{{NoteTag|原文：{{lang-en|This is one of the most exhausting concertos in the violin repertoire. It is emotionally intense throughout – even in the soft passages – and the technical challenges are immense, so it is physically demanding as well. I always warm up for at least 45 minutes before playing this piece, slowly working through the tricky passages until I feel comfortable.}}}}<ref name=":15" />
*[[陳銳_(小提琴家)|陈锐]]：柴可夫斯基的《小提琴协奏曲》受到[[芭蕾|芭蕾]]的很大影响。想想《[[胡桃夹子_(芭蕾舞剧)|胡桃夹子]]》、《[[天鹅湖|天鹅湖]]》、《[[睡美人_(芭蕾舞劇)|睡美人]]》，协奏曲的大部分像是舞蹈，每个故事中都有一个主角。我敢说，这个主角一定是英雄的冒险家，他高尚，他骄傲，还有自我反省的时候。{{NoteTag|原文：{{lang-en|Tchaikovsky's Violin Concerto has a lot of influence from ballet. Think of The Nutcracker, Swan Lake, Sleeping Beauty. Much of the concerto is like a dance and in every story there's a main character. I would say that this this one is definitely the heroic adventurer, one whose character is noble and proud with moments of self-reflection.}}}}<ref name=":15" />
*[[約夏·貝爾|約夏·貝爾]]：我们都在试着去弄明白作曲家想要表达什么，这是个有待解决的大谜团，但同时，我们常忽略他实际告诉我们的80%的内容！{{NoteTag|原文：{{lang-en|We are all trying to figure out what the composer wanted; it's this big mystery we are trying to solve. Meanwhile we are usually ignoring 80 per cent of what he actually did tell us!}}}}<ref name=":15" />
*[[伊扎克·帕尔曼|伊扎克·帕尔曼]]：困难有两种：技术上的，你可以通过练习解决；还有不适。演奏柴可夫斯基是不舒服的，无论你练习多少。{{NoteTag|原文：{{lang-en|There are two types of difficulty: technical difficulty, which you can solve when you practise, and then, of course, discomfort. The Tchaikovsky is uncomfortable to play - no matter how much you practise it.}}}}<ref name=":15" />

